@node MAIN "toolbar_plugin: Introduction"


    @{b}toolbar_plugin@{ub}

        by @{b}Ali Graham@{ub} <agraham@hal9000.net.au>



    @{b}toolbar_plugin@{ub} is a PLUGIN that places
    several gadgets in a horizontal or vertical row,
    and calls a specified function when one of them
    is pressed.

    ------------------------------------------------------------

    @{"  " link TOOLBAR_CONSTRUCTOR}  Constructor

    @{"  " link TOOLBAR_METHODS}  Methods

    @{"  " link TOOLBAR_TAGS}  Tags

    @{"  " link TOOLBAR_EXCEPTIONS}  Exceptions

    @{"  " link TOOLBAR_HISTORY}  History
    
@endnode

@node TOOLBAR_CONSTRUCTOR "toolbar_plugin: Constructors / Destructor"

   @{BG shine}Constructor@{BG back}

      @{b}toolbar(@{"tags" link TOOLBAR_TAGS}=NIL:PTR TO tagitem)@{ub}

      For creating a new plugin object use for example:
      @{FG fill}
      DEF toolbar:PTR TO toolbar_plugin
      NEW toolbar.toolbar([..., TAG_DONE])
      @{FG text}

@endnode

@node TOOLBAR_METHODS "toolbar_plugin: New Methods"

   @{b}set(@{"tag" link TOOLBAR_TAGS}, value)@{ub}

      By calling this method it's possible to change attributes
      at runtime. You can use all tags with the S flag set.
      This method can also be used before the GUI is created and when
      the window is closed.
      Value is a LONG and contains the argument for the used tag.
      @{FG fill}
      Example:
      DEF toolbar:PTR TO toolbar_plugin
      ...
      NEW toolbar.toolbar([..., TAG_DONE])
      ...
      toolbar.set(PLA_ToolBar_Disabled, TRUE)
      ...
      @{FG text}

   @{b}value,check:=get(@{"tag" link TOOLBAR_TAGS})@{ub}

      This method is the counterpart to set. All tags with G flag
      can be used. Argument is the tag you want to get. Return values
      are the requested value and as second a boolean value. So if
      check is FALSE the used tag can't be get.

      @{FG fill}...
      value,check:=toolbar.get(PLA_ToolBar_Disabled)
      ...@{FG text}

      After this:
       value=TRUE
       check=TRUE

      But if you try:

      @{FG fill}...
      value,check:=toolbar.get(PLA_ToolBar_DisplayAll)
      ...@{FG text}

      Then you get this:
       value:=-1
       check:=FALSE


@endnode

@node TOOLBAR_TAGS "toolbar_plugin: Tags"
 The letters [ISG] show you when the tags can be used.
 I = @{"Initalisation" link TOOLBAR_CONSTRUCTOR}
 S = @{"Set Method" link TOOLBAR_METHODS}
 G = @{"Get Method" link TOOLBAR_METHODS 18}


    @{FG shine}PLA_ToolBar_Contents@{FG text}       [I..]

        The text contents of the gadgets in the toolbar; this
        should be passed in as a list of strings, e.g.

        [PLA_ToolBar_Contents,  ['First', 'Second', 'Third'],
         TAG_DONE]


    @{FG shine}PLA_ToolBar_Disabled@{FG text}       [ISG]

        Disable or enable the toolbar. Setting this tag causes the
        gadgets to become disabled; they are all ghosted.


    @{FG shine}PLA_ToolBar_DisplayAll@{FG text}     [I..]

        Setting this tag forces the PLUGIN to display all
        of the gadgets. The default for this tag is FALSE;
        this means that the PLUGIN will show a minimum of
        one gadget, and more depending on how much space
        it is allocated.


    @{FG shine}PLA_ToolBar_Font@{FG text}           [I.G]

        The font that the gadgets should all use. This
        is a pointer to a @{b}textattr@{ub} structure which
        represents an available font. Default is NIL;
        this means that the PLUGIN will use the
        window's font.


    @{FG shine}PLA_ToolBar_Function@{FG text}       [IS.]

        The address of a function which will be called
        when a button on the toolbar is pressed, passed
        in like this:

            @{FG shine}PLA_ToolBar_Function,   {toolbar_pressed},@{FG text}

        The function should be of the form

            @{FG shine}PROC toolbar_pressed(toolbar:PTR TO toolbar_plugin, gad_num)@{FG text}

        @{FG shine}toolbar@{FG text} will be a PTR to the PLUGIN that was pressed,
        and @{FG shine}gad_num@{FG text} will be the number of the gadget that was
        pressed, with the first gadget being 1 (not 0).


    @{FG shine}PLA_ToolBar_Vertical@{FG text}       [I..]
    
        Boolean; whether or not the toolbar will be
        placed vertically. Defaults to FALSE.

@endnode

